# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: z-transform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:z-transform/advanced-z-transform] In mathematics and signal processing, the **advanced z-transform** is an extension of the z-transform, to incorporate ideal delays that are not multiples of the sampling time.
[src:z-transform/advanced-z-transform] The advanced z-transform is widely applied, for example, to accurately model processing delays in digital control.
[src:z-transform/advanced-z-transform] It is also known as the **modified z-transform**.
[src:z-transform/advanced-z-transform] If the delay parameter, *m*, is considered fixed then all the properties of the z-transform hold for the advanced z-transform.
[src:z-transform/advanced-z-transform] which is clearly just the *z*-transform of $f(t)$ .
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The **bilinear transform** (also known as **Tustin's method**, after Arnold Tustin) is used in digital signal processing and discrete-time control theory to transform continuous-time system representations to discrete-time and vice versa.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] It maps positions on the $j\omega$ axis, $\mathrm {Re} [s]=0$ , in the s-plane to the unit circle, $|z|=1$ , in the z-plane.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] This means that for every feature that one sees in the frequency response of the analog filter, there is a corresponding feature, with identical gain and phase shift, in the frequency response of the digital filter but, perhaps, at a somewhat different frequency.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The change in frequency is barely noticeable at low frequencies but is quite evident at frequencies close to the Nyquist frequency.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The bilinear transform is a first-order Padé approximant of the natural logarithm function that is an exact mapping of the *z*-plane to the *s*-plane.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] where T is the numerical integration step size of the trapezoidal rule used in the bilinear transform derivation; or, in other words, the sampling period.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The above bilinear approximation can be solved for s or a similar approximation for $s=(1/T)\ln(z)$ can be performed.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] A continuous-time causal filter is stable if the poles of its transfer function fall in the left half of the complex s-plane.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] A discrete-time causal filter is stable if the poles of its transfer function fall inside the unit circle in the complex z-plane.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The bilinear transform maps the left half of the complex s-plane to the interior of the unit circle in the z-plane.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Thus, filters designed in the continuous-time domain that are stable are converted to filters in the discrete-time domain that preserve that stability.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Likewise, a continuous-time filter is minimum-phase if the zeros of its transfer function fall in the left half of the complex s-plane.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] A discrete-time filter is minimum-phase if the zeros of its transfer function fall inside the unit circle in the complex z-plane.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Then the same mapping property assures that continuous-time filters that are minimum-phase are converted to discrete-time filters that preserve that property of being minimum-phase.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Consider then the pole-zero form of the continuous-time transfer function $H_{a}(s)={\frac {(s-\xi _{1})(s-\xi _{2})\cdots (s-\xi _{Q})}{(s-p_{1})(s-p_{2})\cdots (s-p_{P})}}$ The roots of the numerator and denominator polynomials, *ξi* and *pi*, are the zeros and poles of the system.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] As an example take a simple low-pass RC filter.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The coefficients of the denominator are the 'feed-backward' coefficients and the coefficients of the numerator are the 'feed-forward' coefficients used for implementing a real-time digital filter.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] It is possible to relate the coefficients of a continuous-time, analog filter with those of a similar discrete-time digital filter created through the bilinear transform process.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Normally the constant term in the denominator must be normalized to 1 before deriving the corresponding difference equation.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Again, the constant term in the denominator is generally normalized to 1 before deriving the corresponding difference equation.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] To determine the frequency response of a continuous-time filter, the transfer function $H_{a}(s)$ is evaluated at $s=j\omega _{a}$ which is on the $j\omega$ axis.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Likewise, to determine the frequency response of a discrete-time filter, the transfer function $H_{d}(z)$ is evaluated at $z=e^{j\omega _{d}T}$ which is on the unit circle, $|z|=1$ .
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The bilinear transform maps the $j\omega$ axis of the *s*-plane (which is the domain of $H_{a}(s)$ ) to the unit circle of the *z*-plane, $|z|=1$ (which is the domain of $H_{d}(z)$ ), but it is **not** the same mapping $z=e^{sT}$ which also maps the $j\omega$ axis to the unit circle.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] When the actual frequency of $\omega _{d}$ is input to the discrete-time filter designed by use of the bilinear transform, then it is desired to know at what frequency, $\omega _{a}$ , for the continuous-time filter that this $\omega _{d}$ is mapped to.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] This shows that every point on the unit circle in the discrete-time filter z-plane, $z=e^{j\omega _{d}T}$ is mapped to a point on the $j\omega$ axis on the continuous-time filter s-plane, $s=j\omega _{a}$ .
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The discrete-time filter behaves at frequency $\omega _{d}$ the same way that the continuous-time filter behaves at frequency $(2/T)\tan(\omega _{d}T/2)$ .
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] Specifically, the gain and phase shift that the discrete-time filter has at frequency $\omega _{d}$ is the same gain and phase shift that the continuous-time filter has at frequency $(2/T)\tan(\omega _{d}T/2)$ .
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] This means that every feature, every "bump" that is visible in the frequency response of the continuous-time filter is also visible in the discrete-time filter, but at a different frequency.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] For low frequencies (that is, when $\omega _{d}\ll 2/T$ or $\omega _{a}\ll 2/T$ ), then the features are mapped to a *slightly* different frequency; $\omega _{d}\approx \omega _{a}$ .
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] One can also see that there is a nonlinear relationship between $\omega _{a}$ and $\omega _{d}.$ This effect of the bilinear transform is called **frequency warping**.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The continuous-time filter can be designed to compensate for this frequency warping by setting $\omega _{a}={\frac {2}{T}}\tan \left(\omega _{d}{\frac {T}{2}}\right)$ for every frequency specification that the designer has control over (such as corner frequency or center frequency).
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] This is called **pre-warping** the filter design.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] It is possible, however, to compensate for the frequency warping by pre-warping a frequency specification $\omega _{0}$ (usually a resonant frequency or the frequency of the most significant feature of the frequency response) of the continuous-time system.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] These pre-warped specifications may then be used in the bilinear transform to obtain the desired discrete-time system.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] This is a modified version of Tustin's transform shown above.
[src:z-transform/bilinear-transform] The main advantage of the warping phenomenon is the absence of aliasing distortion of the frequency response characteristic, such as observed with Impulse invariance.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In signal processing, a **digital filter** is a system that performs mathematical operations on a sampled, discrete-time signal to reduce or enhance certain aspects of that signal.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] This is in contrast to the other major type of electronic filter, the analog filter, which is typically an electronic circuit operating on continuous-time analog signals.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A digital filter system usually consists of an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) to sample the input signal, followed by a microprocessor and some peripheral components such as memory to store data and filter coefficients etc.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Program Instructions (software) running on the microprocessor implement the digital filter by performing the necessary mathematical operations on the numbers received from the ADC.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In some high performance applications, an FPGA or ASIC is used instead of a general purpose microprocessor, or a specialized digital signal processor (DSP) with specific paralleled architecture for expediting operations such as filtering.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters may be more expensive than an equivalent analog filter due to their increased complexity, but they make practical many designs that are impractical or impossible as analog filters.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters can often be made very high order, and are often finite impulse response filters, which allows for linear phase response.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters are commonplace and an essential element of everyday electronics such as radios, cellphones, and AV receivers.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A digital filter is characterized by its transfer function, or equivalently, its difference equation.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Mathematical analysis of the transfer function can describe how it will respond to any input.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] As such, designing a filter consists of developing specifications appropriate to the problem (for example, a second-order low-pass filter with a specific cut-off frequency), and then producing a transfer function that meets the specifications.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] where the order of the filter is the greater of *N* or *M*.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] See *Z*-transform's LCCD equation for further discussion of this transfer function.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] This is the form for a recursive filter, which typically leads to an infinite impulse response (IIR) behaviour, but if the denominator is made equal to unity, i.e. no feedback, then this becomes a finite impulse response (FIR) filter.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A variety of mathematical techniques may be employed to analyze the behavior of a given digital filter.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Many of these analysis techniques may also be employed in designs, and often form the basis of a filter specification.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Typically, one characterizes filters by calculating how they will respond to a simple input such as an impulse.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] One can then extend this information to compute the filter's response to more complex signals.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] The impulse response, often denoted $h[k]$ or $h_{k}$ , is a measurement of how a filter will respond to the Kronecker delta function.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] For example, given a difference equation, one would set $x_{0}=1$ and $x_{k}=0$ for $k\neq 0$ and evaluate.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] The impulse response is a characterization of the filter's behavior.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters are typically considered in two categories: infinite impulse response (IIR) and finite impulse response (FIR).
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] IIR filters on the other hand are recursive, with the output depending on both current and previous inputs as well as previous outputs.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Plotting the impulse response reveals how a filter responds to a sudden, momentary disturbance.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] While it is possible for a recursive filter to have a finite impulse response, a non-recursive filter always has a finite impulse response.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] An example is the moving average (MA) filter, which can be implemented both recursively and non recursively.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In discrete-time systems, the digital filter is often implemented by converting the transfer function to a linear constant-coefficient difference equation (LCCD) via the Z-transform.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] The discrete frequency-domain transfer function is written as the ratio of two polynomials.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] The coefficients of the denominator, $a_{k}$ , are the 'feed-backward' coefficients and the coefficients of the numerator are the 'feed-forward' coefficients, $b_{k}$ .
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] This equation shows how to compute the next output sample, $y[n]$ , in terms of the past outputs, $y[n-p]$ , the present input, $x[n]$ , and the past inputs, $x[n-p]$ .
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Applying the filter to an input in this form is equivalent to a Direct Form I or II (see below) realization, depending on the exact order of evaluation.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Although filters are easily understood and calculated, the practical challenges of their design and implementation are significant and are the subject of much advanced research.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] There are two categories of digital filter: the recursive filter and the nonrecursive filter.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] These are often referred to as IIR filters and FIR filters, respectively.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] After a filter is designed, it must be *realized* by developing a signal flow diagram that describes the filter in terms of operations on sample sequences.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A given transfer function may be realized in many ways.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Consider how a simple expression such as $ax+bx+c$ could be evaluated – one could also compute the equivalent $x(a+b)+c$ .
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In the same way, all realizations may be seen as *factorizations* of the same transfer function, but different realizations will have different numerical properties.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Specifically, some realizations are more efficient in terms of the number of operations or storage elements required for their implementation, and others provide advantages such as improved numerical stability and reduced round-off error.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Some structures are better for fixed-point arithmetic and others may be better for floating-point arithmetic.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A straightforward approach for IIR filter realization is direct form I, where the difference equation is evaluated directly.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] This form is practical for small filters, but may be inefficient and impractical (numerically unstable) for complex designs.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In general, this form requires 2N delay elements (for both input and output signals) for a filter of order N.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] The alternate direct form II only needs *N* delay units, where *N* is the order of the filter – potentially half as much as direct form I.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] This structure is obtained by reversing the order of the numerator and denominator sections of Direct Form I, since they are in fact two linear systems, and the commutativity property applies.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Then, one will notice that there are two columns of delays ( $z^{-1}$ ) that tap off the center net, and these can be combined since they are redundant, yielding the implementation as shown below.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] The disadvantage is that direct form II increases the possibility of arithmetic overflow for filters of high *Q* or resonance.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] It has been shown that as *Q* increases, the round-off noise of both direct form topologies increases without bounds.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] This is because, conceptually, the signal is first passed through an all-pole filter (which normally boosts gain at the resonant frequencies) before the result of that is saturated, then passed through an all-zero filter (which often attenuates much of what the all-pole half amplifies).
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A common strategy is to realize a higher-order (greater than 2) digital filter as a cascaded series of second-order *biquadratric* (or *biquad*) sections (see digital biquad filter).
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] The advantage of this strategy is that the coefficient range is limited.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Cascading direct form II sections results in *N* delay elements for filters of order *N*.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Cascading direct form I sections results in *N* + 2 delay elements, since the delay elements of the input of any section (except the first section) are redundant with the delay elements of the output of the preceding section.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters are not subject to the component tolerances, temperature variations, and non-linearities that greatly complicate the design of analog filters.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Analog filters consist of imperfect electronic components, whose values may also change with temperature and drift with time.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] As the order of an analog filter increases, and thus its component count, the effect of variable component errors is greatly magnified.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In digital filters, the coefficient values are stored in computer memory, making them far more stable and predictable.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Because the coefficients of digital filters are definite, they can be used to achieve much more complex and selective designs – specifically with digital filters, one can achieve a lower passband ripple, faster transition, and higher stopband attenuation than is practical with analog filters.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Even if the design could be achieved using analog filters, the engineering cost of designing an equivalent digital filter would likely be much lower.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Furthermore, one can readily modify the coefficients of a digital filter to make an adaptive filter or a user-controllable parametric filter.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] While these techniques are possible in an analog filter, they are again considerably more difficult.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters can be used in the design of finite impulse response filters which can achieve extremely steep rolloff slopes with no phase shift.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Analog filters that perform the same function are often significantly more complicated, as they would require many delay elements.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters rely less on analog circuitry, potentially allowing for a better signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A digital filter will introduce noise to a signal during analog low pass filtering, analog to digital conversion, digital to analog conversion and may introduce digital noise due to quantization.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] With analog filters, every component is a source of thermal noise (such as Johnson noise), so as the filter complexity grows, so does the noise.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] However, digital filters do introduce a higher fundamental latency to the system.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In an analog filter, latency is often negligible; strictly speaking it is the time for an electrical signal to propagate through the filter circuit.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] In digital systems, latency is introduced not only by delay elements in the digital signal path, but also by analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog converters that are required for a system to process analog signals.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital filters must also deal with quantization and rounding errors.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Additionally, in very simple cases or in cases where frequencies and filter slopes are fixed, it is more cost effective to use an analog filter.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Introducing a digital filter requires considerable overhead circuitry, as previously discussed, including two low pass analog filters.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Analog filters also require substantially less power than digital filters and are therefore the only solution when power requirements are tight.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] When making an electrical circuit on a PCB it is generally easier to use a digital solution, because the processing units are highly optimized over the years.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Making the same circuit with analog components would take up a lot more space when using discrete components.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Two alternatives are FPAAs and ASICs, but they are expensive for low quantities.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A filter can be represented by a block diagram, which can then be used to derive a sample processing algorithm to implement the filter with hardware instructions.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A filter may also be described as a difference equation, a collection of zeros and poles or an impulse response or step response.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] These filters give O(n log n) computational costs whereas conventional digital filters tend to be O(n2).
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Another form of a digital filter is that of a state-space model.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] A well used state-space filter is the Kalman filter published by Rudolf Kálmán in 1960.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Traditional linear filters are usually based on attenuation.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Alternatively nonlinear filters can be designed, including energy transfer filters, which allow the user to move energy in a designed way so that unwanted noise or effects can be moved to new frequency bands either lower or higher in frequency, spread over a range of frequencies, split, or focused.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Energy transfer filters complement traditional filter designs and introduce many more degrees of freedom in filter design.
[src:z-transform/digital-filter] Digital energy transfer filters are relatively easy to design and to implement and exploit nonlinear dynamics.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In mathematics, the **discrete-time Fourier transform** (**DTFT**) is a form of Fourier analysis that is applicable to a sequence of discrete values.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The DTFT is often used to analyze samples of a continuous function.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The term *discrete-time* refers to the fact that the transform operates on discrete data, often samples whose interval has units of time.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] From uniformly spaced samples it produces a function of frequency that is a periodic summation of the continuous Fourier transform of the original continuous function.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In simpler terms, when you take the DTFT of regularly-spaced samples of a continuous signal, you get repeating (and possibly overlapping) copies of the signal's frequency spectrum, spaced at intervals corresponding to the sampling frequency.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Under certain theoretical conditions, described by the sampling theorem, the original continuous function can be recovered perfectly from the DTFT and thus from the original discrete samples.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The DTFT itself is a continuous function of frequency, but discrete samples of it can be readily calculated via the discrete Fourier transform (DFT) (see § Sampling the DTFT), which is by far the most common method of modern Fourier analysis.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The inverse DTFT reconstructs the original sampled data sequence, while the inverse DFT produces a periodic summation of the original sequence.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The fast Fourier transform (FFT) is an algorithm for computing one cycle of the DFT, and its inverse produces one cycle of the inverse DFT.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Let $s(t)$ be a continuous function in the time domain.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] We can reduce the integral into a summation by sampling $s(t)$ at intervals of T seconds (see Fourier transform § Numerical integration of a series of ordered pairs).
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Specifically, we can replace $s(t)$ with a discrete sequence of its samples, $s(nT)$ , for integer values of n , and replace the differential element $dt$ with the sampling period T .
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] This Fourier series (in frequency) is a continuous periodic function, whose periodicity is the sampling frequency $1/T$ .
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The subscript $1/T$ distinguishes it from the continuous Fourier transform $S(f)$ , and from the angular frequency form of the DTFT.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The components of the periodic summation are centered at integer values (denoted by k ) of a normalized frequency (cycles per sample).
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Ordinary/physical frequency (cycles per second) is the product of k and the sample-rate, $f_{s}=1/T.$ For sufficiently large $f_{s},$ the $k=0$ term can be observed in the region $[-f_{s}/2,f_{s}/2]$ with little or no distortion (aliasing) from the other terms.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] **Fig.1** depicts an example where $1/T$ is not large enough to prevent aliasing.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The modulated Dirac comb function is a mathematical abstraction sometimes referred to as *impulse sampling*.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] An operation that recovers the discrete data sequence from the DTFT function is called an *inverse DTFT*.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The $s_{_{N}}$ sequence is the inverse DFT.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Thus, our sampling of the DTFT causes the inverse transform to become periodic.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The array of $|S_{k}|^{2}$ values is known as a *periodogram*, and the parameter N is called NFFT in the Matlab function of the same name.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In order to evaluate one cycle of $s_{_{N}}$ numerically, we require a finite-length $s[n]$ sequence.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] For instance, a long sequence might be truncated by a window function of length L resulting in three cases worthy of special mention.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] For notational simplicity, consider the $s[n]$ values below to represent the values modified by the window function.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Recall that decimation of sampled data in one domain (time or frequency) produces overlap (sometimes known as aliasing) in the other, and vice versa.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Compared to an L -length DFT, the $s_{_{N}}$ summation/overlap causes decimation in frequency, leaving only DTFT samples least affected by spectral leakage.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] That is usually a priority when implementing an FFT filter-bank (channelizer).
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] With a conventional window function of length $L,$ scalloping loss would be unacceptable.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] So multi-block windows are created using FIR filter design tools.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Their frequency profile is flat at the highest point and falls off quickly at the midpoint between the remaining DTFT samples.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The larger the value of parameter $I,$ the better the potential performance.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] When a symmetric, L -length window function ( s ) is truncated by 1 coefficient it is called *periodic* or *DFT-even*.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] That is a common practice, but the truncation affects the DTFT (spectral leakage) by a small amount.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] It is at least of academic interest to characterize that effect.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] An N -length DFT of the truncated window produces frequency samples at intervals of $1/N,$ instead of $1/L.$ The samples are real-valued, but their values do not exactly match the DTFT of the symmetric window.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The periodic summation, $s_{_{N}},$ along with an N -length DFT, can also be used to sample the DTFT at intervals of $1/N.$ Those samples are also real-valued and do exactly match the DTFT (example: File:Sampling the Discrete-time Fourier transform.svg).
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] To use the full symmetric window for spectral analysis at the $1/N$ spacing, one would combine the $n=0$ and $n=N$ data samples (by addition, because the symmetrical window weights them equally) and then apply the truncated symmetric window and the N -length DFT.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In order to take advantage of a fast Fourier transform algorithm for computing the DFT, the summation is usually performed over all N terms, even though $N-L$ of them are zeros.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Therefore, the case $L<N$ is often referred to as **zero-padding**.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Spectral leakage, which increases as L decreases, is detrimental to certain important performance metrics, such as resolution of multiple frequency components and the amount of noise measured by each DTFT sample.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] But those things don't always matter, for instance when the $s[n]$ sequence is a noiseless sinusoid (or a constant), shaped by a window function.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Then it is a common practice to use *zero-padding* to graphically display and compare the detailed leakage patterns of window functions.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] An important special case is the circular convolution of sequences s and y defined by $s_{_{N}}*y,$ where $s_{_{N}}$ is a periodic summation.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The significance of this result is explained at circular convolution and fast convolution algorithms.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] $S_{2\pi }(\omega )$ is a Fourier series that can also be expressed in terms of the bilateral Z-transform.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] where the $S_{z}$ notation distinguishes the Z-transform from the Fourier transform.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Note that when parameter T changes, the terms of $S_{2\pi }(\omega )$ remain a constant separation $2\pi$ apart, and their width scales up or down.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The terms of *S*1/*T*(*f*) remain a constant width and their separation 1/*T* scales up or down.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Some common transform pairs are shown in the table below.
[src:z-transform/discrete-time-fourier-transform] This table shows some mathematical operations in the time domain and the corresponding effects in the frequency domain.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] In mathematics, the **radius of convergence** of a power series is the radius of the largest disk at the center of the series in which the series converges.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] It is either a non-negative real number or $\infty$ .
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] When it is positive, the power series converges absolutely and uniformly on compact sets inside the open disk of radius equal to the radius of convergence, and it is the Taylor series of the analytic function to which it converges.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] On the boundary, that is, where |*z* − *a*| = *r*, the behavior of the power series may be complicated, and the series may converge for some values of z and diverge for others.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] The radius of convergence is infinite if the series converges for all complex numbers z.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] The radius of convergence can be found by applying the root test to the terms of the series.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] The root test states that the series converges if *C* < 1 and diverges if *C* > 1.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] and diverges if the distance exceeds that number; this statement is the Cauchy–Hadamard theorem.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] Note that *r* = 1/0 is interpreted as an infinite radius, meaning that *f* is an entire function.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] The limit involved in the ratio test is usually easier to compute, and when that limit exists, it shows that the radius of convergence is finite.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] Usually, in scientific applications, only a finite number of coefficients $c_{n}$ are known.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] Typically, as n increases, these coefficients settle into a regular behavior determined by the nearest radius-limiting singularity.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] In this case, two main techniques have been developed, based on the fact that the coefficients of a Taylor series are roughly exponential with ratio $1/r$ where r is the radius of convergence.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] A power series with a positive radius of convergence can be made into a holomorphic function by taking its argument to be a complex variable.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] cannot be defined in a way that makes it holomorphic.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] The set of all points whose distance to *a* is strictly less than the radius of convergence is called the *disk of convergence*.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] has no singularities on the real line, since $1+z^{2}$ has no real roots.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] The root test shows that its radius of convergence is 1.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] In accordance with this, the function *f*(*z*) has singularities at ±*i*, which are at a distance 1 from 0.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] For a proof of this theorem, see analyticity of holomorphic functions.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] It is easy to apply the root test in this case to find that the radius of convergence is 1.
