[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] However, in applications, one is often interested in the precision of a numerical answer.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] Both the number of terms and the value at which the series is to be evaluated affect the accuracy of the answer.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] For example, if we want to calculate sin(0.1) accurate up to five decimal places, we only need the first two terms of the series.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] However, if we want the same precision for *x* = 1 we must evaluate and sum the first five terms of the series.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] For sin(10), one requires the first 18 terms of the series, and for sin(100) we need to evaluate the first 141 terms.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] So for these particular values the fastest convergence of a power series expansion is at the center, and as one moves away from the center of convergence, the rate of convergence slows down until you reach the boundary (if it exists) and cross over, in which case the series will diverge.
[src:z-transform/region-of-convergence] Such a series converges if the real part of *s* is greater than a particular number depending on the coefficients *a**n*: the abscissa of convergence.
[src:z-transform/star-transform] In applied mathematics, the **starred transform**, or **star transform**, is a discrete-time variation of the Laplace transform, so-named because of the asterisk or "star" in the customary notation of the sampled signals.
[src:z-transform/star-transform] where $\delta _{T}(t)$ is a Dirac comb function, with period of time T.
[src:z-transform/star-transform] The starred transform is a convenient mathematical abstraction that represents the Laplace transform of an *impulse sampled* function $x^{*}(t)$ , which is the output of an *ideal sampler*, whose input is a continuous function, $x(t)$ .
[src:z-transform/star-transform] The starred transform is similar to the Z transform, with a simple change of variables, where the starred transform is explicitly declared in terms of the sampling period (T), while the Z transform is performed on a discrete signal and is independent of the sampling period.
[src:z-transform/star-transform] This makes the starred transform a de-normalized version of the one-sided Z-transform, as it restores the dependence on sampling parameter *T*.
[src:z-transform/star-transform] This line integration is equivalent to integration in the positive sense along a closed contour formed by such a line and an infinite semicircle that encloses the poles of X(s) in the left half-plane of *p*.
[src:z-transform/star-transform] Alternatively, the aforementioned line integration is equivalent to integration in the negative sense along a closed contour formed by such a line and an infinite semicircle that encloses the infinite poles of ${\frac {1}{1-e^{-T(s-p)}}}$ in the right half-plane of *p*.
[src:z-transform/star-transform] This substitution restores the dependence on *T*.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] In mathematics and signal processing, the **Z-transform** converts a discrete-time signal, which is a sequence of real or complex numbers, into a complex valued frequency-domain (the **z-domain** or **z-plane**) representation.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] It can be considered a discrete-time counterpart of the Laplace transform (the *s-domain* or *s-plane*).
[src:z-transform/z-transform] This similarity is explored in the theory of time-scale calculus.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] While the continuous-time Fourier transform is evaluated on the s-domain's vertical axis (the imaginary axis), the discrete-time Fourier transform is evaluated along the z-domain's unit circle.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] The s-domain's left half-plane maps to the area inside the z-domain's unit circle, while the s-domain's right half-plane maps to the area outside of the z-domain's unit circle.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] In signal processing, one of the means of designing digital filters is to take analog designs, subject them to a bilinear transform which maps them from the s-domain to the z-domain, and then produce the digital filter by inspection, manipulation, or numerical approximation.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] Such methods tend not to be accurate except in the vicinity of the complex unity, i.e. at low frequencies.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] The basic idea now known as the Z-transform was known to Laplace, and it was re-introduced in 1947 by W.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] Hurewicz and others as a way to treat sampled-data control systems used with radar.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] It gives a tractable way to solve linear, constant-coefficient difference equations.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] It was later dubbed "the z-transform" by Ragazzini and Zadeh in the sampled-data control group at Columbia University in 1952.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] The modified or advanced Z-transform was later developed and popularized by E.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] The idea contained within the Z-transform is also known in mathematical literature as the method of generating functions which can be traced back as early as 1730 when it was introduced by de Moivre in conjunction with probability theory.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] From a mathematical view the Z-transform can also be viewed as a Laurent series where one views the sequence of numbers under consideration as the (Laurent) expansion of an analytic function.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] The Z-transform can be defined as either a *one-sided* or *two-sided* transform (similarly to the one-sided Laplace transform and the two-sided Laplace transform).
[src:z-transform/z-transform] where n is an integer and z is, in general, a complex number.
