[src:z-transform/z-transform] Through the bilinear transformation, the complex *s*-plane (of the Laplace transform) is mapped to the complex z-plane (of the z-transform).
[src:z-transform/z-transform] While this mapping is (necessarily) nonlinear, it is useful in that it maps the entire $i\omega$ axis of the *s*-plane onto the unit circle in the z-plane.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] As such, the Fourier transform (which is the Laplace transform evaluated on the $i\omega$ axis) becomes the discrete-time Fourier transform.
[src:z-transform/z-transform] This assumes that the Fourier transform exists; i.e., that the $i\omega$ axis is in the region of convergence of the Laplace transform.
